2.1 Select only the top 10 worst arrival delays for each day for each month for each year. Using the subset of the data, calculate the average delay for each month regardless of the dates or years.

Hints: you will want to group the data by year, month, and day. Then, you will want to ungroup the data to remove the groupings and do another grouping to calculate means by month.

Code 
library(tidyverse)
library(nycflights13)

top_10_delays <- flights %>%
  group_by(year, month, day) %>%
  arrange(desc(arr_delay)) %>%
  slice_max(arr_delay, n = 10, with_ties = FALSE) %>%
  ungroup()

avg_monthly_delays <- top_10_delays %>%
  group_by(month) %>%
  summarize(avg_delay = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE))

print(avg_monthly_delays)

2.2 Visualize the data that shows average delays each month. Style the chart appropriately, as you learned in the previous modules, to make the chart presentable.

Code 
avg_monthly_delays %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = factor(month, labels = month.abb), y = avg_delay, fill = avg_delay)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(
    title = "Average Arrival Delays by Month",
    x = "Month",
    y = "Average Delay (minutes)"
  ) +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "skyblue", high = "darkred", name = "Delay (min)") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 14) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face = "bold"),
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 0.6),
    legend.position = "top"
  )

relig_income_longer <- relig_income %>%

library(nycflights13)
library(dplyr)
library(gt)
daily_departures <- flights %>%
  filter(!is.na(dep_time)) %>% 
  group_by(year, month, day) %>%
  summarize(
    first_dep = min(dep_time, na.rm = TRUE),
    last_dep = max(dep_time, na.rm = TRUE),
    n = n()
  ) %>%
  ungroup()
latest_first_departures <- daily_departures %>%
  group_by(year, month) %>%

  ungroup() %>%

  ) %>%

    month = "Month",

        • 1. To create the total monthly temperature, count the number of months weighted by Temp.

        • 2. Change Monthâs data from numeric value to associated character: from 5 to âMayâ, 6 to âJuneâ, 7 to âJulyâ, 8 to âAugustâ, and 9 to âSeptemberâ.

        • 3. Convert Month to a factor.

        • 4. Reorder Month by the size of the total temperature in descending order.Â 

Code 
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
air.tib %>%
  group_by(Month) %>% 
  summarise(total_temp = sum(Temp, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%  
  mutate(
    Month = recode(Month, 
                   `5` = "May", 
                   `6` = "June", 
                   `7` = "July", 
                   `8` = "August", 
                   `9` = "September"),  
    Month = factor(Month, levels = Month[order(-total_temp)])  
  ) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = total_temp, y = Month, fill = Month)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", show.legend = FALSE) +  
  labs(
    title = "Monthly Total Temperature",
    x = "Total Temperature",
    y = "Month"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() + 
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 16, face = "bold"),
    axis.title.x = element_text(size = 12),
    axis.title.y = element_text(size = 12)
  )
